04696nam a22005415i 9780773550780DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735507807 a10.1515/97807735507802doi  a(DE-B1597)655815  a(OCoLC)988865869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060202bisacsh1 aMcGowan, Mark G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImperial Irish :bCanada’s Irish Catholics Fight the Great War, 1914-1918 /cMark G. McGowan. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b10 b&w photos, 1 map, 23 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v7800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tThe Complicated Worlds of Canada’s Irish Catholics -- tThe Long Road to War -- t“Let All Come to the Battle” -- tNed Murray’s War -- tIrreligion, Immorality, and Blasphemy -- tBetween Resistance and Rebellion -- tWinning the War, Saving the Peace -- tThe Principles and Outcomes of War -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1914 and 1918, many Irish Catholics in Canada found themselves in a vulnerable position. Not only was the Great War slaughtering millions, but tension and violence was mounting in Ireland over the question of independence from Britain and Home Rule. For Canada’s Irish Catholics, thwarting Prussian militarism was a way to prove that small nations, like Ireland, could be free from larger occupying countries. Yet, even as tens of thousands of Irish Catholic men and women rallied to the call to arms and supported government efforts to win the war, many Canadians still doubted their loyalty to the Empire. Retracing the struggles of Irish Catholics as they fought Canada’s enemies in Europe while defending themselves against charges of disloyalty at home, The Imperial Irish explores the development and fraying of interfaith and intercultural relationships between Irish Catholics, French Canadian Catholics, and non-Catholics throughout the course of the Great War. Mark McGowan contrasts Irish Canadian Catholics' beliefs with the neutrality of Pope Benedict XV, the supposed pro-Austrian sympathies of many immigrants from central Europe, Irish republicans inciting rebellion in Ireland, and the perceived indifference to the war by French Canadian Catholics, and argues that, for the most part, Irish Catholics in Canada demonstrated strong support for the imperial war effort by recruiting in large numbers. He further investigates their religious lives within the Canadian Expeditionary Force, the spiritual resources available to them, and church and lay leaders’ negotiation of the sensitive political developments in Ireland that coincided with the war effort. Grounded in research from dozens of archives as well as census data and personnel records, The Imperial Irish explores stirring conflicts that threatened to irreparably divide Canada along religious and linguistic lines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCatholicszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIrishzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355078040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773550780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978077355078